article.description:
Whether contact by Nuggets center Nikola Jokic with Scott Brooks during a timeout in the waning moments was intentional -- or even embellished by the Wizards coach --
 depends on who was asked.
article.headline: John Wall: Nikola Jokic's bump of coach 'something you don't do'
article.linkText: Wall cries foul over Jokic's bump of Wiz coach
article.story:
DENVER -- Scott Brooks took what basically amounted to a late-game charge.

That's right, the coach of the Washington Wizards.

Brooks stepped onto the court after a timeout with 32 seconds remaining and was bumped into by Denver Nuggets center Nikola Jokic, who was on his way to the bench. Jokic was assessed a technical foul in a strange occurrence that helped the Wizards to a 109-104 win Monday night.

"That's something you don't do," Wizards star John Wall said. "No matter what's going on between the players or teammates, that's something you don't do to a coach. It's like me calling a coach a certain name. But hopefully he'll apologize."

Whether it was intentional by Jokic -- or even embellished on the part of the Wizards coach -- depends on who's asked.

"It was an awkward, weird situation. I don't think [Jokic] did it on purpose, but it happened," Brooks said. "I've never had that happen before."

Bradley Beal made the technical free throw, increasing the Wizards' lead to 105-102. Beal then sealed the victory with a driving layup.

After the game, Jokic said he was upset about being pushed from behind just before the timeout and was just making his way back to the Nuggets' bench.

"I tried to look at the score and hit ... the coach," Jokic said. "I'm sorry because I put my team in a bad position."

Jokic's coach had his back.

"I just watched it 10 times. Nikola said he didn't do it intentional," Michael Malone said. "Nikola is walking off the court. Scott Brooks is walking on the court. There's contact made. It was embellished a little, to be honest, I think.

"I don't think it was intentional either. Scott Brooks is a very good coach and a good guy. Things happen in the heat of the moment you can't always explain."

In an interview with a pool reporter, crew chief Derrick Stafford said the officials assessed a technical because Jokic "intentionally walked into Scotty Brooks on his way to the bench."

Beal scored 20 points as all five Washington starters reached double figures. Wall finished with 19 points as he struggled from the floor (3-of-13) but made up for it on the free throw line (13-of-15). He added 12 assists as the Wizards improved to 3-0.

Otto Porter Jr. had 17 points and 10 rebounds.

Jokic broke out of a scoring slump with 29 points. His running layup early in the first quarter ended a string of six straight quarters without a point.

"I scored, and we lost. Maybe it's better for me to not score," Jokic said.

TIP-INS

Wizards: F/C Jason Smith missed the game in his home state with a sprained right shoulder. Smith grew up in nearby Kersey and went to school at Colorado State. "He's been wanting to play well and hit 17 3s against them, but it's not going to happen tonight," Brooks said. "He will have to save it for next year." ... F Markieff Morris missed the game as he recovers from sports hernia surgery. ... Kelly Oubre Jr. had nine of his 14 points in the fourth quarter.

Nuggets: F Juancho Hernangomez was out with an illness. ... F Richard Jefferson dressed but didn't play. He signed a one-year deal last week. ... F Paul Millsap finished with 17 points. ... The Nuggets have dropped three straight to the Wizards. ... G Emmanuel Mudiay had 15 points off the bench.

TURNOVERS

The Wizards took advantage of 24 turnovers and finished 26-of-28 from the free throw line.

"We showed glimpses of our defense at times," Wall said. "We're a long, active team. We can put pressure on teams in the pick-and-roll and trust and help each other. We turn teams over and get more possessions."

QUOTABLE

"John Wall is in attack mode every minute he's on the floor. He's playing downhill, playing north-and-south and getting to the basket. ... We have to show a crowd to him all night long, to take away those driving lanes," Malone said of stopping Wall.

UP NEXT

Wizards: At the Los Angeles Lakers on Wednesday for their second contest on a four-game West Coast swing.

Nuggets: Play in Charlotte on Wednesday against Dwight Howard and the Hornets.

Information from The Associated Press was used in this report.
